# Workflow & Git Conventions

Full guide: [CONTRIBUTING.md](../../CONTRIBUTING.md)

## Branches

| Branch | Purpose |
| ------ | ------- |
| `main` | Stable default — merge only via PR |
| `feat/<scope>` | Feature or roadmap phase step (kebab-case) |
| `fix/<scope>` | Bugfix |
| `chore/<scope>` | Tooling, docs, rules |
| `docs/<scope>` | Documentation only |

**Do not** push directly to `main`.

## Commits (Conventional Commits, English)

```
<type>(<scope>): <imperative subject>

[optional body — why, not what]
```

Types: `feat`, `fix`, `docs`, `chore`, `refactor`, `test`, `ci`, `build`

**Rules:**

- One logical topic per commit
- Subject lowercase, no trailing period, ~72 chars max
- Code commits: `pnpm lint` and `pnpm build` must pass

## Pull requests

- Required before merge to `main` (solo dev: PR = review checkpoint)
- PR title matches commit style — use [.github/pull_request_template.md](../../.github/pull_request_template.md)
- Keep PRs small and single-topic

## Agent rules

- Never push to `main` directly
- Never mix unrelated changes (e.g. ADRs + feature code in one commit)
- **Docs before code** when schema or architecture changes
- Update ADRs when changing architecture (see `docs/adr/`)
- Align `.cursor/rules/` after stack or workflow changes
- Respect active roadmap phase in `docs/implementation-roadmap.md`
- No secrets in commits; Secretlint runs on pre-commit
- `AGENTS.md` is canonical for Claude Code and Codex — do not duplicate rules elsewhere
